# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gaussian-quadrature
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Briefly, the function $f(x)$ to be integrated is evaluated at the N extrema or roots of a Chebyshev polynomial and these values are used to construct a polynomial approximation for the function.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] This polynomial is then integrated exactly.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] In practice, the integration weights for the value of the function at each node are precomputed, and this computation can be performed in $O(N\log N)$ time by means of fast Fourier transform-related algorithms for the DCT.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] A simple way of understanding the algorithm is to realize that Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature (proposed by those authors in 1960) amounts to integrating via a change of variable *x* = cos(*θ*).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The algorithm is normally expressed for integration of a function *f*(*x*) over the interval [−1,1] (any other interval can be obtained by appropriate rescaling).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] That is, we have transformed the problem from integrating $f(x)$ to one of integrating $f(\cos \theta )\sin \theta$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] one must again perform a numeric integration, so at first this may not seem to have simplified the problem.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] for $k=0,\ldots ,N$ and then use the formula above for the integral in terms of these $a_{k}$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] From this formula, it is clear that the Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature rule is symmetric, in that it weights *f*(*x*) and *f*(−*x*) equally.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Because of aliasing, one only computes the coefficients $a_{2k}$ up to *k* = *N*/2, since discrete sampling of the function makes the frequency of 2*k* indistinguishable from that of *N*–2*k*.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Equivalently, the $a_{2k}$ are the amplitudes of the unique bandlimited trigonometric interpolation polynomial passing through the *N*+1 points where *f*(cos *θ*) is evaluated, and we approximate the integral by the integral of this interpolation polynomial.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] and thus we are "really" integrating $f(x)$ by integrating its approximate expansion in terms of Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The evaluation points $x_{n}=\cos(n\pi /N)$ correspond to the extrema of the Chebyshev polynomial $T_{N}(x)$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The fact that such Chebyshev approximation is just a cosine series under a change of variables is responsible for the rapid convergence of the approximation as more terms $T_{k}(x)$ are included.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] A cosine series converges very rapidly for functions that are even, periodic, and sufficiently smooth.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] This is true here, since $f(\cos \theta )$ is even and periodic in $\theta$ by construction, and is *k*-times differentiable everywhere if $f(x)$ is *k*-times differentiable on $[-1,1]$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Fejér proposed two quadrature rules very similar to Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature, but much earlier (in 1933).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Of these two, Fejér's "second" quadrature rule is nearly identical to Clenshaw–Curtis.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The only difference is that the endpoints $f(-1)$ and $f(1)$ are set to zero.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] That is, Fejér only used the *interior* extrema of the Chebyshev polynomials, i.e. the true stationary points.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Fejér's "first" quadrature rule evaluates the $a_{k}$ by evaluating $f(\cos \theta )$ at a different set of equally spaced points, halfway between the extrema: $\theta _{n}={\bigl (}n+{\tfrac {1}{2}}{\bigr )}\pi {\big /}N$ for $0\leq n<N$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] These are the *roots* of $T_{N}(\cos \theta )$ , and are known as the Chebyshev nodes.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] However, Fejér's first quadrature rule is not nested: the evaluation points for 2*N* do not coincide with any of the evaluation points for *N*, unlike Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature or Fejér's second rule.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Despite the fact that Fejér discovered these techniques before Clenshaw and Curtis, the name "Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature" has become standard.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The classic method of Gaussian quadrature evaluates the integrand at $N+1$ points and is constructed to *exactly* integrate polynomials up to degree $2N+1$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] In contrast, Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature, above, evaluates the integrand at $N+1$ points and exactly integrates polynomials only up to degree $N+1$ (assuming N is an even number).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] It may seem, therefore, that Clenshaw–Curtis is intrinsically worse than Gaussian quadrature, but in reality this does not seem to be the case.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] In practice, several authors have observed that Clenshaw–Curtis can have accuracy comparable to that of Gaussian quadrature for the same number of points.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] This is possible because most numeric integrands are not polynomials (especially since polynomials can be integrated analytically), and approximation of many functions in terms of Chebyshev polynomials converges rapidly (see Chebyshev approximation).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] In fact, recent theoretical results argue that both Gaussian and Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature have error bounded by $O([2N]^{-k}/k)$ for a *k*-times differentiable integrand.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] One often cited advantage of Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature is that the quadrature weights can be evaluated in $O(N\log N)$ time by fast Fourier transform algorithms (or their analogues for the DCT), whereas most algorithms for Gaussian quadrature weights required $O(N^{2})$ time to compute.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] However, recent algorithms have attained $O(N)$ complexity for Gauss–Legendre quadrature.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] As a practical matter, high-order numeric integration is rarely performed by simply evaluating a quadrature formula for very large N .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Instead, one usually employs an adaptive quadrature scheme that first evaluates the integral to low order, and then successively refines the accuracy by increasing the number of sample points, possibly only in regions where the integral is inaccurate.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] To evaluate the accuracy of the quadrature, one compares the answer with that of a quadrature rule of even lower order.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Ideally, this lower-order quadrature rule evaluates the integrand at a *subset* of the original *N* points, to minimize the integrand evaluations.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] This is called a nested quadrature rule, and here Clenshaw–Curtis has the advantage that the rule for order *N* uses a subset of the points from order 2*N*.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] In contrast, Gaussian quadrature rules are not naturally nested, and so one must employ Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formulas or similar methods.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Nested rules are also important for sparse grids in multidimensional quadrature, and Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature is a popular method in this context.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The most common case is $w(x)=1$ , as above, but in certain applications a different weight function is desirable.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The basic reason is that, since $w(x)$ can be taken into account *a priori*, the integration error can be made to depend only on the accuracy in approximating $f(x)$ , regardless of how badly behaved the weight function might be.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature can be generalized to this case as follows.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] As before, it works by finding the cosine-series expansion of $f(\cos \theta )$ via a DCT, and then integrating each term in the cosine series.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] For most $w(x)$ , this integral cannot be computed analytically, unlike before.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Since the same weight function is generally used for many integrands $f(x)$ , however, one can afford to compute these $W_{k}$ numerically to high accuracy beforehand.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Moreover, since $w(x)$ is generally specified analytically, one can sometimes employ specialized methods to compute $W_{k}$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] For example, special methods have been developed to apply Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature to integrands of the form $f(x)w(x)$ with a weight function $w(x)$ that is highly oscillatory, e.g. a sinusoid or Bessel function (see, e.g., Evans & Webster, 1999).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] This is useful for high-accuracy Fourier series and Fourier–Bessel series computation, where simple $w(x)=1$ quadrature methods are problematic because of the high accuracy required to resolve the contribution of rapid oscillations.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Here, the rapid-oscillation part of the integrand is taken into account via specialized methods for $W_{k}$ , whereas the unknown function $f(x)$ is usually better behaved.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Another case where weight functions are especially useful is if the integrand is unknown but has a known singularity of some form, e.g. a known discontinuity or integrable divergence (such as 1/√*x*) at some point.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] In this case the singularity can be pulled into the weight function $w(x)$ and its analytical properties can be used to compute $W_{k}$ accurately beforehand.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Note that Gaussian quadrature can also be adapted for various weight functions, but the technique is somewhat different.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] In Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature, the integrand is always evaluated at the same set of points regardless of $w(x)$ , corresponding to the extrema or roots of a Chebyshev polynomial.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] In Gaussian quadrature, different weight functions lead to different orthogonal polynomials, and thus different roots where the integrand is evaluated.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] It is also possible to use Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature to compute integrals of the form ${\textstyle \int _{0}^{\infty }f(x)\,dx}$ and ${\textstyle \int _{-\infty }^{\infty }f(x)\,dx}$ , using a coordinate-remapping technique.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] High accuracy, even exponential convergence for smooth integrands, can be retained as long as $f(x)$ decays sufficiently quickly as |*x*| approaches infinity.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] to transform an infinite or semi-infinite interval into a finite one, as described in Numerical integration.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] There are also additional techniques that have been developed specifically for Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The factor multiplying sin(*θ*), *f*(...)/(...)2, can then be expanded in a cosine series (approximately, using the discrete cosine transform) and integrated term-by-term, exactly as was done for *f*(cos *θ*) above.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] To eliminate the singularity at *θ*=0 in this integrand, one merely requires that *f*(*x*) go to zero sufficiently fast as *x* approaches infinity, and in particular *f*(*x*) must decay at least as fast as 1/*x*3/2.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Note that the quadrature rule does not include the endpoints, where we have assumed that the integrand goes to zero.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The formula above requires that *f*(*x*) decay faster than 1/*x*2 as *x* goes to ±∞.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] (If *f* decays exactly as 1/*x*2, then the integrand goes to a finite value at the endpoints and these limits must be included as endpoint terms in the trapezoidal rule.).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] Because of the endpoint singularities in this coordinate remapping, however, one uses Fejér's first quadrature rule [which does not evaluate *f*(−1)] unless *g*(∞) is finite.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] In practice, it is inconvenient to perform a DCT of the sampled function values ⁠ $f(\cos \theta )$ ⁠ for each new integrand.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] These weights $w_{n}$ are also computed by a DCT, as is easily seen by expressing the computation in terms of matrix algebra.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] As discussed above, because of aliasing, there is no point in computing coefficients beyond $a_{N}$ , so *D* is an ${\bigl (}{\tfrac {1}{2}}N+1{\bigr )}\times {\bigl (}{\tfrac {1}{2}}N+1{\bigr )}$ matrix.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] (These weight factors are altered if one changes the DCT matrix ⁠ D ⁠ to use a different normalization convention.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/clenshaw-curtis-quadrature] The weights $w_{n}$ are positive and their sum is equal to one.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-hermite-quadrature] where *n* is the number of sample points used.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-hermite-quadrature] Consider a function *h(y)*, where the variable *y* is normally distributed: $y\sim {\mathcal {N}}(\mu ,\sigma ^{2})$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-hermite-quadrature] – i.e. the average of the function's values one standard deviation below and above the mean.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] The **Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formula** is an adaptive method for numerical integration.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] It is a variant of Gaussian quadrature, in which the evaluation points are chosen so that an accurate approximation can be computed by re-using the information produced by the computation of a less accurate approximation.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] It is an example of what is called a nested quadrature rule: for the same set of function evaluation points, it has two quadrature rules, one higher order and one lower order (the latter called an *embedded* rule).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] The difference between these two approximations is used to estimate the calculational error of the integration.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] Like the Gaussian quadrature method it is based on, Gauss-Kronrod curvature assumes the integrand is a polynomial and will not converge rapidly over intervals where the integrand is not infinitely smooth.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] These formulas are named after Alexander Kronrod, who invented them in the 1960s, and Carl Friedrich Gauss.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] where *w**i*, are the weights and *x**i* are points at which to evaluate the function *f*(*x*).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] If the interval [*a*, *b*] is subdivided, the Gauss evaluation points of the new subintervals never coincide with the previous evaluation points (except at the midpoint for odd numbers of evaluation points), and thus the integrand must be evaluated at every point.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] Gauss–Kronrod formulas are extensions of the Gauss quadrature formulas generated by adding $n+1$ points to an n -point rule in such a way that the resulting rule is exact for polynomials of degree less than or equal to $3n+1$ (Laurie (1997, p.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] 1133); the corresponding Gauss rule is of order $2n-1$ ).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] These extra points are the zeros of Stieltjes polynomials.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] This allows for computing higher-order estimates while reusing the function values of a lower-order estimate.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] The difference between a Gauss quadrature rule and its Kronrod extension is often used as an estimate of the approximation error.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] A popular example combines a 7-point Gauss rule with a 15-point Kronrod rule (Kahaner, Moler & Nash 1989, §5.5).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] Because the Gauss points are incorporated into the Kronrod points, a total of only 15 function evaluations are needed.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] The integral is then estimated by the Kronrod rule $K15$ and the error can be estimated as $|G7-K15|$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] Patterson (1968) showed how to find further extensions of this type, Piessens & Branders (1974) and Monegato (1978) proposed improved algorithms, and finally the most efficient algorithm was proposed by Laurie (1997).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] Quadruple precision (34 decimal digits) coefficients for (G7, K15), (G10, K21), (G15, K31), (G20, K41) and others are computed and tabulated.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-kronrod-quadrature-formula] Routines for Gauss–Kronrod quadrature are provided by the QUADPACK library, the GNU Scientific Library, the NAG Numerical Libraries, R, the C++ library Boost., as well as the Julia package QuadGK.jl (which can compute Gauss–Kronrod formulas to arbitrary precision).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-laguerre-quadrature] For the last integral one then uses Gauss-Laguerre quadrature.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-laguerre-quadrature] Note, that while this approach works from an analytical perspective, it is not always numerically stable.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-laguerre-quadrature] This allows one to efficiently evaluate such integrals for polynomial or smooth *f*(*x*) even when α is not an integer.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] In numerical analysis, **Gauss–Legendre quadrature** is a form of Gaussian quadrature for approximating the definite integral of a function.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] This choice of quadrature weights *w**i* and quadrature nodes *x**i* is the unique choice that allows the quadrature rule to integrate degree 2*n* − 1 polynomials exactly.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Many algorithms have been developed for computing Gauss–Legendre quadrature rules.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] The Golub–Welsch algorithm presented in 1969 reduces the computation of the nodes and weights to an eigenvalue problem which is solved by the QR algorithm.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] This algorithm was popular, but significantly more efficient algorithms exist.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Algorithms based on the Newton–Raphson method are able to compute quadrature rules for significantly larger problem sizes.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] In 2014, Ignace Bogaert presented explicit asymptotic formulas for the Gauss–Legendre quadrature weights and nodes, which are accurate to within double-precision machine epsilon for any choice of *n* ≥ 21.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] This allows for computation of nodes and weights for values of *n* exceeding one billion.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Carl Friedrich Gauss was the first to derive the Gauss–Legendre quadrature rule, doing so by a calculation with continued fractions in 1814.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] He calculated the nodes and weights to 16 digits up to order *n*=7 by hand.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi discovered the connection between the quadrature rule and the orthogonal family of Legendre polynomials.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] As there is no closed-form formula for the quadrature weights and nodes, for many decades people were only able to hand-compute them for small *n*, and computing the quadrature had to be done by referencing tables containing the weight and node values.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] By 1942 these values were only known for up to *n*=16.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] For integrating *f* over $[-1,1]$ with Gauss–Legendre quadrature, the associated orthogonal polynomials are Legendre polynomials, denoted by *P**n*(*x*).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Some low-order quadrature rules are tabulated below for integrating over $[-1,1]$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] For integrating over a general real interval $[a,b]$ , a change of interval can be applied to convert the problem to one of integrating over $[-1,1]$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Several researchers have developed algorithms for computing Gauss–Legendre quadrature nodes and weights based on the Newton–Raphson method for finding roots of functions.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Various optimizations for this specific problem are used.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] For instance, some methods compute $\theta _{i}=\arccos x_{i}$ to avoid issues associated with clustering of the roots $x_{i}$ near the ends of the interval $-1$ and 1 .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Some methods utilize formulas to approximate the weights and then use a few iterations of Newton-Raphson to lower the error of the approximation to below machine precision.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] In 1969, Golub and Welsch published their method for computing Gaussian quadrature rules given the three term recurrence relation that the underlying orthogonal polynomials satisfy.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] They reduce the problem of computing the nodes of a Gaussian quadrature rule to the problem of finding the eigenvalues of a particular symmetric tridiagonal matrix.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] The QR algorithm is used to find the eigenvalues of this matrix.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] By taking advantage of the symmetric tridiagonal structure, the eigenvalues can be computed in ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ time, as opposed to the ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ time expected for a generic eigenvalue problem.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Various methods have been developed that use approximate closed-form expressions to compute the nodes.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] As mentioned above, in some methods formulas are used as approximations to the nodes, after which some Newton-Raphson iterations are performed to refine the approximation.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] In a 2014 paper, Ignace Bogaert derives asymptotic formulas for the nodes that are exact up to machine precision for $n\geq 21$ and for the weights that are exact up to machine precision for $n\geq 30$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] This method does not require any Newton-Raphson iterations or evaluations of Bessel functions as other methods do.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] As shown in the paper, the method was able to compute the nodes at a problem size of one billion in 11 seconds.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Since the nodes near the endpoints of $[-1,1]$ become very close to each other at this problem size, this method of computing the nodes is sufficient for essentially any practical application in double-precision floating point.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Johansson and Mezzarobba describe a strategy to compute Gauss–Legendre quadrature rules in arbitrary-precision arithmetic, allowing both small and large n .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] A rule of order $n=1000$ with 1000 digits of precision can be calculated in around one second.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Their method uses Newton–Raphson iteration together with several different techniques for evaluating Legendre polynomials.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] The algorithm also provides a certified error bound.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Gil, Segura and Temme describe iterative methods with fourth order convergence for the computation of Gauss–Jacobi quadratures (and, in particular, Gauss–Legendre).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] The methods do not require a priori estimations of the nodes to guarantee its fourth-order convergence.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Computations of quadrature rules with even millions of nodes and thousands of digits become possible in a typical laptop.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Gauss–Legendre quadrature is optimal in a very narrow sense for computing integrals of a function *f* over [−1, 1], since no other quadrature rule integrates all degree 2*n* − 1 polynomials exactly when using *n* sample points.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] However, this measure of accuracy is not generally a very useful one---polynomials are very simple to integrate and this argument does not by itself guarantee better accuracy on integrating other functions.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature is based on approximating *f* by a polynomial interpolant at Chebyshev nodes and integrates polynomials of degree up to *n* exactly when given *n* samples.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Even though it does not integrate polynomials or other functions that are analytic in a large neighborhood of [−1, 1] as well as Gauss–Legendre quadrature, Clenshaw–Curtis converges at approximately the same rate as Gauss–Legendre quadrature for most (non-analytic) integrands.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Also, Clenshaw–Curtis shares the properties that Gauss–Legendre quadrature enjoys of convergence for all continuous integrands f and robustness to numerical rounding errors.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Clenshaw–Curtis is straightforward to implement in ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ time by FFT-based methods.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Newton–Cotes quadrature is based on approximating *f* by a polynomial interpolant at equally-spaced points in [−1, 1], and like Clenshaw–Curtis also integrates polynomials of degree up to *n* exactly when given *n* samples.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] However, it suffers from Runge's phenomenon as *n* increases; Newton–Cotes does not converge for some continuous integrands *f*, and when it does converge it may suffer from numerical rounding errors.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gauss-legendre-quadrature] Thus, both Clenshaw–Curtis and Gauss–Legendre enjoy substantial benefits over Newton–Cotes for moderate to large *n*.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] In numerical analysis, an n-point **Gaussian quadrature rule**, named after Carl Friedrich Gauss, is a quadrature rule constructed to yield an exact result for polynomials of degree 2*n* − 1 or less by a suitable choice of the nodes xi and weights wi for *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] The modern formulation using orthogonal polynomials was developed by Carl Gustav Jacobi in 1826.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] which is exact for polynomials of degree 2*n* − 1 or less.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] This exact rule is known as the Gauss–Legendre quadrature rule.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] The quadrature rule will only be an accurate approximation to the integral above if *f* (*x*) is well-approximated by a polynomial of degree 2*n* − 1 or less on [−1, 1].
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] The Gauss–Legendre quadrature rule is not typically used for integrable functions with endpoint singularities.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] where *g*(*x*) is well-approximated by a low-degree polynomial, then alternative nodes xi' and weights wi' will usually give more accurate quadrature rules.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] One may also want to integrate over semi-infinite (Gauss–Laguerre quadrature) and infinite intervals (Gauss–Hermite quadrature).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] It can be shown (see Press et al., or Stoer and Bulirsch) that the quadrature nodes xi are the roots of a polynomial belonging to a class of orthogonal polynomials (the class orthogonal with respect to a weighted inner-product).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] This is a key observation for computing Gauss quadrature nodes and weights.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] For the simplest integration problem stated above, i.e., *f*(*x*) is well-approximated by polynomials on $[-1,1]$ , the associated orthogonal polynomials are Legendre polynomials, denoted by *P**n*(*x*).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Some low-order quadrature rules are tabulated below (over interval [−1, 1], see the section below for other intervals).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] An integral over [*a*, *b*] must be changed into an integral over [−1, 1] before applying the Gaussian quadrature rule.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Change the limits so that one can use the weights and abscissae given in Table 1.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Also, find the absolute relative true error.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] The integration problem can be expressed in a slightly more general way by introducing a positive weight function ω into the integrand, and allowing an interval other than [−1, 1].
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] That is, the problem is to calculate $\int _{a}^{b}\omega (x)\,f(x)\,dx$ for some choices of a, b, and ω.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] For *a* = −1, *b* = 1, and *ω*(*x*) = 1, the problem is the same as that considered above.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Other choices lead to other integration rules.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Equation numbers are given for Abramowitz and Stegun (A & S).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Note that this will be true for all the orthogonal polynomials above, because each pn is constructed to be orthogonal to the other polynomials pj for *j*<*n*, and *x**k* is in the span of that set.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] If we pick the n nodes xi to be the zeros of pn, $p_{n}\propto \prod _{i=1}^{n}(x-x_{i})$ , then there exist n weights wi which make the Gaussian quadrature computed integral exact for all polynomials *h*(*x*) of degree 2*n* − 1 or less.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Furthermore, all these nodes xi will lie in the open interval (*a*, *b*).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] To prove the first part of this claim, let *h*(*x*) be any polynomial of degree 2*n* − 1 or less.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Since pn is by assumption orthogonal to all monomials of degree less than n, it must be orthogonal to the quotient *q*(*x*).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] where *w**i*, the weight associated with the node *x**i*, is defined to equal the weighted integral of *l**i*(*x*) (see below for other formulas for the weights).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] But all the xi are roots of pn, so the division formula above tells us that $h(x_{i})=p_{n}(x_{i})\,q(x_{i})+r(x_{i})=r(x_{i}),$ for all i.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] This proves that for any polynomial *h*(*x*) of degree 2*n* − 1 or less, its integral is given exactly by the Gaussian quadrature sum.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] To prove the second part of the claim, consider the factored form of the polynomial *p**n*.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Any complex conjugate roots will yield a quadratic factor that is either strictly positive or strictly negative over the entire real line.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Any factors for roots outside the interval from a to b will not change sign over that interval.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] This polynomial cannot change sign over the interval from a to b because all its roots there are now of even multiplicity.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] But *p**n* is orthogonal to all polynomials of degree *n* − 1 or less, so the degree of the product $\prod _{i}(x-x_{i})$ must be at least n.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Therefore *p**n* has n distinct roots, all real, in the interval from a to b.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] This integral expression for $w_{i}$ can be expressed in terms of the orthogonal polynomials $p_{n}(x)$ and $p_{n-1}(x)$ as follows.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] We can evaluate the integral on the right hand side for $q(x)=p_{n-1}(x)$ as follows.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] The term in the brackets is a polynomial of degree $n-2$ , which is therefore orthogonal to $p_{n-1}(x)$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] According to equation (**2**), the weights are obtained by dividing this by $p'_{n}(x_{i})$ and that yields the expression in equation (**1**).
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] $w_{i}$ can also be expressed in terms of the orthogonal polynomials $p_{n}(x)$ and now $p_{n+1}(x)$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Consider the following polynomial of degree $2n-2$ $f(x)=\prod _{\begin{smallmatrix}1\leq j\leq n\\j\neq i\end{smallmatrix}}{\frac {\left(x-x_{j}\right)^{2}}{\left(x_{i}-x_{j}\right)^{2}}}$ where, as above, the xj are the roots of the polynomial $p_{n}(x)$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Since the degree of $f(x)$ is less than $2n-1$ , the Gaussian quadrature formula involving the weights and nodes obtained from $p_{n}(x)$ applies.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Since both $\omega (x)$ and $f(x)$ are non-negative functions, it follows that $w_{i}>0$ .
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] There are many algorithms for computing the nodes xi and weights wi of Gaussian quadrature rules.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] The most popular are the Golub-Welsch algorithm requiring *O*(*n*2) operations, Newton's method for solving $p_{n}(x)=0$ using the three-term recurrence for evaluation requiring *O*(*n*2) operations, and asymptotic formulas for large *n* requiring *O*(*n*) operations.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] First of all, the polynomials defined by the recurrence relation starting with $p_{0}(x)=1$ have leading coefficient one and correct degree.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Given the starting point by $p_{0}$ , the orthogonality of $p_{r}$ can be shown by induction.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] However, if the scalar product satisfies $(xf,g)=(f,xg)$ (which is the case for Gaussian quadrature), the recurrence relation reduces to a three-term recurrence relation: For $s<r-1,xp_{s}$ is a polynomial of degree less than or equal to *r* − 1.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] On the other hand, $p_{r}$ is orthogonal to every polynomial of degree less than or equal to *r* − 1.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] The zeros $x_{j}$ of the polynomials up to degree n, which are used as nodes for the Gaussian quadrature can be found by computing the eigenvalues of this matrix.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] This procedure is known as *Golub–Welsch algorithm*.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] See, for instance, (Gil, Segura & Temme 2007) for further details.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] The error of a Gaussian quadrature rule can be stated as follows.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Stoer and Bulirsch remark that this error estimate is inconvenient in practice, since it may be difficult to estimate the order 2*n* derivative, and furthermore the actual error may be much less than a bound established by the derivative.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Another approach is to use two Gaussian quadrature rules of different orders, and to estimate the error as the difference between the two results.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] For this purpose, Gauss–Kronrod quadrature rules can be useful.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] If the interval [*a*, *b*] is subdivided, the Gauss evaluation points of the new subintervals never coincide with the previous evaluation points (except at zero for odd numbers), and thus the integrand must be evaluated at every point.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] *Gauss–Kronrod rules* are extensions of Gauss quadrature rules generated by adding *n* + 1 points to an n-point rule in such a way that the resulting rule is of order 2*n* + 1.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] This allows for computing higher-order estimates while re-using the function values of a lower-order estimate.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] In some applications, it is desirable to have quadrature rules that have the high accuracy of Gauss formulas, but that also include the end points of the interval among the evaluation points.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Such rules are known as **Gauss–Lobatto**, or simply **Lobatto quadrature**, named after Dutch mathematician Rehuel Lobatto.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Because for an *n* point rule, one can no longer freely choose the locations of all quadrature points (2 of the points are fixed at the end points), one needs to expect that the rule is less accurate than regular Gaussian quadrature.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Indeed, an *n* point Gauss-Lobatto rule is only accurate for polynomials up to degree 2*n* − 3.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] Abscissas: xi is the $(i-1)$ st zero of $P'_{n-1}(x)$ , here $P_{m}(x)$ denotes the standard Legendre polynomial of m-th degree and the dash denotes the derivative.
[src:gaussian-quadrature/gaussian-quadrature] An adaptive variant of this algorithm with 2 interior nodes is found in GNU Octave and MATLAB as `quadl` and `integrate`.
